[[File:Pony Express Bible 1858.jpg|thumb|Pony Express Bible, [[KJV]] of 1858]] [[File:Pony Express 1858 bible lettering.jpg|thumb|Pony Express Bible with gold lettering]] [[File:Holy Bible 1858.jpg|thumb|American Bible Society KJV 1858]] [[File:Overland Mail Bible 2.jpg|thumb|Overland Mail Company Bible]] [[File:Overland Mail Bible 1.jpg|thumb|Close up showing gold lettering]] [[File:ABS1859.jpg|thumb|Overland Mail Company Bible title page]]
''' The Pony Express Bible ''' is a Protestant Bible that was distributed to the [[Pony Express|Pony Express riders]] in 1860 and 1861.
== Description == The special edition leather-bound Bible was given to all the employees by the operators [[Russell, Majors and Waddell]].{{sfn|Godfrey|1994|p=62|}}{{sfn|Chapman|1932|p=300|}} Its dimensions are about 5.7 inches (14.5&nbsp;cm) tall by 3.6 inches (9.1&nbsp;cm) wide and a little over 2 inches thick.{{sfn|Newberry Library|1968|p=46}}{{sfn|Heritage Auctions|2010|p=95}} It has 1,278 double-columned pages.<ref name=Ephemera>{{cite web |url=http://ephemera.ning.com/photo/original-russell-majors-waddell-pony-express-bible-1858 |title=Original Russell, Majors & Waddell "Pony Express Bible," 1858|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 2014|website= The Ephemera Network |publisher= Mike Ferguson|accessdate=2014-05-05}}</ref>
The copies of the Bible were specifically commissioned by [[Alexander Majors]] and contained full versions of both the Old and New Testaments. The firm had originally purchased these special copies for their company's wagon-train employees.{{sfn|Livingston|1948|p=46}} The Bibles had gold lettering on the cover with a contemporary inscription and the wording, "Presented by Russell, Majors & Waddell. 1858".{{sfn|Parke-Bernet Galleries|1947|p=9}} The source for the Old and New Testaments was an 1858 [[King James Version]] published by the [[American Bible Society]] in New York City.{{sfn|Newberry Library|1968|p=46}}
On commencing employment, a Pony Express rider was given one of the special edition Bibles.{{sfn|Corbett|2003|p=46 ''Alexander Majors of the great freight-hauling firm of Russell, Majors & Waddell, which underwrote this venture, gave every employee a little calfskin-bound Bible, although the curious often wondered how a man riding a horse at a gallop from St. Joseph, Missouri, to Sacramento, California, would have had occasion for Bible study'' }} The rider had to swear to and sign the ''frontier pledge'' of loyalty, honesty, and sobriety,{{sfn|Settle|1975|p=45 ''When the job was done [recruiting], about thirty riders had signed Majors' pledge, given bond for the faithful performance of their duty, and received a little Bible'' }}{{sfn|Guthrie|Smith|2009|p=21}} that was on the inside front cover of the Bible:<ref name=BancroftLibrary>{{cite web |url= http://oskicat.berkeley.edu/record=b10529605~S1 |title= UCB Library Catalog |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014 |website=The Regents of the University of California |publisher= University of California |accessdate=2014-06-07}}</ref>
{{quote|I, ......, do hereby swear, before the Great and Living God, that during my engagement, and while I am an employee of Russell, Majors, and Waddell, I will, under no circumstances, use profane language, that I will drink no intoxicating liquors, that I will not quarrel or fight with any other employee of the firm, and that in every respect I will conduct myself honestly, be faithful to my duties, and so direct all my acts as to win the confidence of my employers, so help me God.|Oath sworn by Pony Express Riders<ref>{{cite book|last=Burton|first=Richard|title=The City of the Saints|year=1862|publisher=Harper & Brothers|location=New York}}</ref> }}
It appears that the 183 riders employed from April 1860 to November 1861 did not take the pledge very seriously as, on the whole, they were considered dreadful, rough and unconventional.{{sfn|Bradley|Smith|1960|p=66}}
== Background == Alexander Majors, one of the original operators of the Pony Express, had religious convictions and required certain principles be held that he related to the Christian Bible.{{sfn|Jeffrey|2010|p=22}}{{sfn|Settle|1975|p=7 ''In writing that pledge and requiring his employees to sign and keep it, Majors was giving expression to his lifelong, stern, Calvinistic Presbyterian sentiments. He read his Bible regularly, attended church when he could, and sought to practice Christian principles in all his relations with other men.'' Note: this was written about his life prior to establishing the Pony Express, but similar pledges were used for the employees of his various companies.}} Examples were not to swear in public or drink intoxicating alcoholic beverages and that each rider was to honor Sunday as a day of rest.<ref name=PostalMuseum>{{cite web |url=http://postalmuseum.si.edu/exhibits/2a5a2_ponyexpress.html |title=Pony Express: Romance versus Reality |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 2014|website=National Postal Museum |publisher= Smithsonian Institution |accessdate=2014-05-05}}</ref> Initially the Pony Express riders were issued certain pieces of equipment to carry, which included a [[bowie knife]], and the Pony Express Bible.<ref name=PonyExpressNevada>{{cite web |url= http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?q1=Pony%20Express%20Bible;id=pur1.32754077529620;view=plaintext;seq=6;start=1;size=10;page=search|title=The Pony Express in Nevada |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1990 |website= |publisher= U.S. Dept. of the Interior, Bureau of Land Management|accessdate=5/3/2014}}</ref> Later, most of this hardware was abandoned because it was too heavy to carry and looked upon as extra unnecessary items for their journey.<ref name=PonyExpressNevada/> Some sources say that the riders carried the Bible given them, at least in the beginning. {{sfn|Jeffrey|2010|p=22}} Other sources say the riders never carried their Bible since it added weight that would slow down the pony they were riding.<ref name=PostalMuseum/> Many of the riders took only a single pistol with an extra cylinder of bullets on their rides.<ref name=PonyExpressNevada/> Some didn't even take a gun, depending instead on the speed of their pony for their greatest defense against hostilities.<ref name=PonyExpressNevada/>
== Locations == The Forty-fifth Annual Report of the American Bible Society shows 300 copies of the Bibles granted May 9, 1861, to Major and Russell by the American Bible Society.<ref name=ABS300>{{cite web |url=http://news.americanbible.org/article/did-abs-print-a-special-pony-express-bible |title=Did ABS Print a Special Pony Express Bible? |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 2014|website= American Bible Society News |publisher= American Bible Society |accessdate=2014-05-07}}</ref> Of as the last record known of a 1960 'census' there were 12 copies left in existence.<ref name=Heritage>{{cite web |url= http://historical.ha.com/c/item.zx?saleNo=6035&lotNo=47280#Photo |title= The Famous 1858 "Pony Express Bible"|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014 |website= |publisher= Heritage Auctions|accessdate=5/3/2014}}</ref> There have been only two of these Bibles that were made available for public purchase since 1980.{{sfn|Heritage Auctions|2010|p=95}}
* 2 copies – Pony Express History and Art Gallery, [[San Rafael, California]] * 2 copies – Daughters of Utah Pioneers, [[Salt Lake City, Utah]] * 1 copy – Bancroft Library, [[Berkeley, California]] * 1 copy – Denver City Library (Main), [[Denver, Colorado]]<ref name=DPL>{{cite web |url=http://catalog.denverlibrary.org/search/title.aspx?ctx=1.1033.0.0.6&cn=159248 |title=Catalog Card Call Number: C220.52 B47ho |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014 |website=DPL Catalog Cards |publisher=Denver Public Library |accessdate=2014-05-21}}</ref> * 1 copy – Mormon Station State Historical Monument, [[Genoa, Nevada]] * 1 copy – Nebraska State Historical Society, [[Lincoln, Nebraska]] * 1 copy – Sons of Utah Pioneers, Salt Lake City, Utah * 1 copy – State Historical Society of Colorado, Denver, Colorado * 1 copy – Society of California Pioneers, [[San Francisco, California]] * 1 copy – The California Historical Society, San Francisco, California
== Society of California Pioneers == <gallery> File:Pony Express Bible SCP1.jpg File:Pony Express Bible SCP3.jpg File:Pony Express Bible SCP2.jpg File:Pony Express Bible SCP4.jpg </gallery> ::::::Pony Express Bible owned by the [[Society of California Pioneers]].
== Overland Mail Company == The [[Pony Express#Pony Express route|Pony Express route]] that the riders used went through the Territories of [[Utah Territory|Utah]], [[Nebraska Territory|Nebraska]] and [[Kansas Territory|Kansas]] sharing relay stations with the [[Butterfield Overland Mail Company]] stagecoach line. The Overland Mail Company eventually did take over the western portion of the Pony Express route that went to [[Sacramento, California]], when the Pony Express firm was dissolved in 1861. The Pony Express route went through what are now the states of Missouri, Kansas, Nebraska, Wyoming, Colorado, Utah, Nevada, and California.<ref name=route>{{cite web |url=http://www.xphomestation.com/xproute.html |title=Pony Express Route |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014 |website=Pony Express History |publisher= |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref>
The Overland Mail Company station operators likely had copies of the American Bible Society's 1859 edition of the Bible similar to the 1858 Pony Express Bible.<ref name=twentyfifth>{{cite web |url=http://clausenbooks.com/bible1900.htm |title= Chronological History of the Bible – 19th Century/1851-1900|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2012 |website= |publisher=Clausen Books |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref>
== ''Pawn Stars'' == On the ''[[Pawn Stars]]'' television program in season 8, episode 55 called [[List of Pawn Stars episodes#Season 8|"Ponies and Phonies"]] (April 24, 2014), the Overland Mail Company Bible is compared to the Pony Express Bible by [[Pawn Stars#Recurring experts|rare book consultant Rebecca Romney]].<ref name=Rebecca>{{cite web |url=http://www.history.com/shows/pawn-stars/episodes |title=History Channel / Pawn Stars / Episodes 2014|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2014 |website=History |publisher=A&E Television Networks |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref>
